  "sourceCode": "Employer Portal",
  "title": "Coating Process Engineer",
  "description": "<p>As a Coating Process Engineer, you will be involved in developing, optimizing, and sustaining thin film coating processes for optical products.</p><p><strong>What You Will Do</strong></p><ul><li>Support the design of optical thin film coatings to meet customer and product requirements.</li><li>Conduct process development, characterization, and optimization for thin film coating processes.</li><li>Handling hands-on processes including optical component cleaning, coating equipment operation, and experimental process trials.</li><li>Operate, set up, and handle thin film coating machines and related equipment, including process execution and first-level troubleshooting.</li><li>Participate in New Product Introduction (NPI) activities, including process trials, data collection, and documentation.</li><li>Support process yield, efficiency, and stability improvement for NPI and mass production products.</li><li>Collaborate with cross-functional teams to resolve process issues.</li><li>Apply DOE, SPC, and statistical analysis to identify root causes and validate process improvements.</li><li>Ensure compliance with internal procedures, quality systems, and safety requirements.</li><li>Prepare technical reports and present findings to the team when required.</li></ul><p><strong>What You Must Have</strong></p><ul><li>Bachelor’s or Master’s Degree in Physics, Materials Science, Chemical Engineering, Photonics Engineering or related disciplines.</li><li>No prior work experience required; however, candidates with up to 2 years of relevant experience will be preferred.</li><li>Strong problem-solving mind-set, with the ability to structure experiments and validate solutions using DOE and data analysis.</li><li>Demonstrated strong self-learning ability to adopt new tools, processes, and technical concepts independently.</li><li>Good communication skills, with the ability to clearly present data-driven findings and collaborate effectively in a team.</li></ul><p><strong>Skills & Experience That Will Be an Advantage</strong></p><ul><li>Exposure to thin film coating, optics, vacuum technology, or surface engineering through coursework, projects, internships, or research.</li><li>Familiarity with optical thin film design software (e.g. MacLeod, FilmStar).</li><li>Basic understanding of SPC and DOE concepts.</li></ul><p></p>",
